:::summary
The Abrahamic religions — Judaism, Christianity, and Islam — are the three great monotheistic faiths that trace their spiritual ancestry to the patriarch **Abraham**, whom God called out of Mesopotamia to establish a covenant that would, through his descendants, ultimately bless all the nations of the earth. Together they are followed by more than half the world's population and have shaped the history, law, philosophy, art, and politics of human civilization more profoundly than any other religious tradition. Understanding the Abrahamic faiths — their shared roots, their deep divisions, and their differing claims — is essential for any educated Christian and any serious student of history.
:::

